{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501260","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501260"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:26:19+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:26:19+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1739"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1739"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.31,0.38,0.02,0.11]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1739"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102597"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1739","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1739"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1739"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85074"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"121"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5294"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6728"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35851"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102597","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102597"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman underwent a total nephrectomy of an upper pole renal lesion after it was incidentally found on a CT abdomen. The CT showed no evidence of metastases. Histology of the lesion showed it to be a T3a clear cell carcinoma with invasion into the renal vein. The resection margins are clear.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following ongoing management options would be most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adjuvant radiotherapy","Adjuvant cytotoxic chemotherapy","Regular surveillance with CT imaging","Annual bone scan","Adjuvant tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapy"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis is a stage 3 renal cell carcinoma. There are four stages:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EI \u2013 Tumour confined within the renal capsule \u0026lt;7 cm diameter\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EII \u2013 Tumour confined within the renal capsule \u0026gt;7 cm diameter\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIII \u2013 Tumour invades the renal vein or inferior vena cava (A), regional lymph node involvement (B), or both (C)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIV \u2013 Tumour invades the adjacent viscera (excluding ipsilateral adrenal) or distant metastases\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe first line management of a stage 3 clear cell renal carcinoma is radical nephrectomy, with curative intent, as has occurred in this case. Following surgery, there is no role for adjuvant \u003Cstrong\u003Eradiotherapy,\u003C/strong\u003E \u003Cstrong\u003Ecytotoxic chemotherapy or tyrosine kinase inhibitor therapy\u003C/strong\u003E as there is there has been no proven benefit for these treatments in the adjuvant setting for what is classified as localised disease (Stages I - III).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile renal cell carcinomas can metastasise to bones, in this case there is no suggestion of metastases and the \u0022curative\u0022 nephrectomy suggests the entire cancer has now been removed. This means the patient has no need for \u003Cstrong\u003Eannual bone scans\u003C/strong\u003E. If a new renal lesion or lesion somewhere else in the body was found, then a bone scan may be warranted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFor patients who undergo surgical resections, whether that be partial or complete, it is accepted practice to do \u003Cstrong\u003Eregular surveillance\u003C/strong\u003E in case new renal cell carcinomas or metastatic disease develops. CT imaging would be the most appropriate form of surveillance. In the case of a 50-year-old patient, the radiation-associated risks associated with CT surveillance would be very low.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Radical nephrectomy is the first line management of stage 1-3 renal cell carcinoma","After surgical resection, regular surveillance should be performed"],"references":["Padala SA, Kallam A. Clear Cell Renal Carcinoma. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; January 2022. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK557644/","Delahunt B, Eble JN, Samaratunga H, et al. Staging of renal cell carcinoma: current progress and potential advances. Pathology . 2021 Jan; 53:120-28."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85074"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1739"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85074","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85074"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-13T09:55:00+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-13T09:55:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1739"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102597"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"g